{{Infobox settlement | official_name = Dilpashar Union | native_name = দিলপাশার ইঊনিয়ন | settlement_type = | image_skyline = | imagesize = | image_alt = | image_caption = | pushpin_map = Bangladesh | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Bangladesh | pushpin_label_position = right | postal_code = [[6640]] | subdivision_type = [[Country]] | subdivision_name = {{flag|Bangladesh}} | subdivision_type1 = | subdivision_name1 = [[Rajshahi Division]] | subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Bangladesh|District]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Pabna District]] | subdivision_type3 = | subdivision_name3 = [[bhangura]] | population_total = 18253 | population_as_of = | population_footnotes = | population_density_km2 = | area_total_km2 = | area_metro_km2 = | elevation_m = | elevation_ft = | leader_title = | leader_name = | leader_title1 = | leader_name1 = | timezone = [[Bangladesh Standard Time|BST]] | utc_offset = +6 | coordinates = {{coord|24.2250|89.4000|type:city_region:BD|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | website = | footnotes = }} '''Dilpashar''' ({{lang-bn|দিলপাশার}}) is a [[Union Councils of Bangladesh|union parishad]] under [[Bhangura Upazila]] of [[Pabna District]] in the [[Rajshahi Division]] of western [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=Banglapedia>{{cite book |last=Musafir |first=Md Nuruzzaman |chapter=Bhangura Upazila |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Bhangura_Upazila |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |editor=Sirajul Islam and Ahmed A. Jamal |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]] |year=2012 |edition=Second}}</ref>
==About== Dilpashar union comprises eight villages. They are [[Chachkia]], [[Kajitol]], [[Betuan]], [[Dilpashar (village)|Dilpashar]], Magura, [[Adabariya]], [[Patul]], [[Laxmikol]]. There is a post office, health center, two secondary schools (B.B. High School & College and Chachkia Govt. Primary School), as well as two bazaars (Betuan and Dilpashar). Renowned Personalities: Abdur Rob Sardar (Ex Chairman), Aminul Islam Khan, Nobo Kumar Gosh, Safiur Rahman, Momtaz, Saiful Islam, Abu Bakkar Khan, Asokh Kumar Prono.{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}}
