{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image=CGS Arctic at anchor in Pond Inlet, 1923.jpg |Ship image size=300px | Ship caption= CGS ''Arctic'' at anchor at [[Pond Inlet]] in 1923 }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header= | Ship country= Germany | Ship flag={{Shipboxflag|Germany|empire}} | Ship name= ''Gauss'' | Ship namesake=[[Carl Friedrich Gauss]] | Ship owner= | Ship operator= | Ship registry= | Ship route= | Ship ordered= | Ship awarded= | Ship builder=[[Howaldtswerke-Deutsche Werft]], [[Kiel]] | Ship original cost=500,000 [[German gold mark|marks]] | Ship yard number= | Ship way number= | Ship laid down= | Ship launched=2 April 1901 | Ship sponsor= | Ship christened= | Ship completed= | Ship acquired= | Ship in service=1901 | Ship out of service=1903 | Ship renamed= | Ship reclassified= | Ship refit= | Ship struck= | Ship reinstated= | Ship homeport= | Ship identification= | Ship motto= | Ship nickname= | Ship honours= | Ship fate=Sold to Canada, 1904 | Ship notes= | Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header=title | Ship country= Canada | Ship flag={{Shipboxflag|Canada|naval-1921}} | Ship name= ''Arctic'' | Ship acquired=by purchase, 1904 | Ship in service=1904 | Ship out of service=1925 | Ship renamed= | Ship reclassified= | Ship refit= | Ship struck= | Ship reinstated= | Ship homeport= | Ship identification= | Ship motto= | Ship nickname= | Ship honours= | Ship captured= | Ship fate=Abandoned, 1925 | Ship notes= | Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header= | Header caption= | Ship type=[[Research vessel|Polar exploration vessel]] | Ship tonnage={{GRT|762}} | Ship displacement= {{Convert|1442|LT|t|0|lk=on|abbr=on}} | Ship length= {{Convert|46|m|ftin|abbr=on}} | Ship beam= {{Convert|11|m|ftin|abbr=on}} | Ship height= | Ship draught={{Convert|4.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}} | Ship depth= | Ship hold depth= | Ship decks= | Ship deck clearance= | Ship ramps= | Ship ice class=A1 | Ship power= | Ship propulsion=1 × {{Convert|325|hp|0|abbr=on}} auxiliary triple expansion steam engine, single screw | Ship sail plan=*[[Barquentine]]-rigged *Area: {{Convert|1000|sqm|abbr=on}}<ref name="schiffe-und-mehr"/> | Ship speed= {{Convert|7|kn|lk=in}} | Ship range= | Ship endurance= | Ship boats= | Ship capacity=700 tons of stores | Ship crew=30 | Ship sensors= | Ship armament= | Ship armour= | Ship notes= }} |}
'''''Gauss''''' was a ship built in Germany specially for polar exploration, named after the [[mathematician]] and [[physical scientist]] [[Carl Friedrich Gauss]]. Purchased by Canada in 1904, the vessel was renamed '''CGS ''Arctic'''''. As ''Arctic'', the vessel made annual trips to the Canadian Arctic until 1925. The ship's fate is disputed among the sources, but all claim that by the mid-1920s, the vessel was out of service.
==Ship construction== [[File:Gauss ship post card.jpg|left|thumb|333x333px|Postcard showing the construction of the Gauss ship]] The ship was built by the [[Howaldtswerke-Deutsche Werft]] shipyard at [[Kiel]]<ref name="gcc">{{cite web |url= http://www.ccg-gcc.gc.ca/eng/CCG/USQUE_Wooden_Shipbuilding |title=Usque Ad Mare – The Last Phase of Wooden Shipbuilding |first=Thomas E.|last= Appleton |work=Canadian Coast Guard |year=2012 |accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> at a cost of 500,000 [[German gold mark|marks]].<ref name="coolantarctica">{{cite web |url=http://www.coolantarctica.com/Antarctica%20fact%20file/History/antarctic_whos_who_gauss.htm |title=German National Antarctic Expedition 1901–03 |work=coolantarctica.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67q1Aeibb?url=http://www.coolantarctica.com/Antarctica%20fact%20file/History/antarctic_whos_who_gauss.htm |archivedate=22 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Ceremonial ship launching|Launched]] on 2 April 1901<ref name="schiffe-und-mehr">{{cite web |url= http://www.schiffe-und-mehr.com/ |title=Expeditionsschiff (Barkentine) ''Gauss'' |work=schiffe-und-mehr.com |year=2012|accessdate=3 August 2012|language=de}}</ref> she was modelled on [[Fridtjof Nansen]]'s ship ''[[Fram]]'', and rigged as a [[barquentine]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://todayinsci.com/V/VonDrygalski_Erich/VonDrygalski-SiegeOfTheSouthPole.htm |title=Chapter XX: Early Expeditions of the Twentieth Century |first=Hugh Robert |last=Mill |work=The Siege Of The South Pole : The Story of Antarctic Exploration |year=1905 |accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> [[Displacement (ship)|Displacing]] {{convert|1,442|LT|t}},<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.antarctic-circle.org/ships.htm |title=Antarctic Ship |first=Robert B. |last=Stephenson |work=antarctic-circle.org |year=2010 |accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> ''Gauss'' had a tonnage of {{GRT|762|disp=long}}.<ref name=miramar>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1116992|shipname=Gauss|accessdate=27 May 2017}}</ref> The ship was {{Convert|46|m|ftin|abbr=on}} long, {{Convert|11|m|ftin|abbr=on}} in the [[Beam (nautical)|beam]], with a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{Convert|4.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}.<ref name="schiffe-und-mehr"/>{{efn|name=measurements}} With a {{Convert|325|hp|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="coolantarctica"/> [[triple expansion steam engine]] driving one [[Propeller|screw]] to augment the sails, she was capable of {{Convert|7|kn|lk=in}}.<ref name="schiffe-und-mehr"/><ref name=maginley>{{cite book |last=Maginley |first=Charles D. |last2=Collin |first2=Bernard |date=2001 |title=The Ships of Canada's Marine Services |publisher=Vanwell Publishing Limited |location=St. Catharines, Ontario |isbn=1-55125-070-5|pages=30}}</ref>{{efn|name=power}}
Classed "A1" by [[Germanischer Lloyd]]s, she was designed to carry 700 tons of stores, enough to make her self-sufficient for up to three years with a crew of 30 aboard. The hull was exceptionally strong, and the rudder and propeller were designed to be hoisted aboard for inspection or repairs.<ref name="gcc"/>
==Ship history== [[File:Gauss corp2854.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of ''Gauss'' in the ice during the German Antarctic Expedition taken using a tethered balloon]]
Between 1901 and 1903 ''Gauss'' explored the [[Antarctic]] in the [[Gauss expedition]] under the leadership of [[Erich von Drygalski]].
In early 1904 the ship was purchased by the Canadian government under the advice of [[Joseph-Elzéar Bernier]], who had surveyed the ship before the acquisition. The ship was renamed ''Arctic'' and under the command of Bernier she explored the [[Canadian Arctic Archipelago|Arctic Archipelago]]. Bernier and ''Arctic'' made annual expeditions to Canada's north.<ref name=maginley/> On 1 July 1909, Bernier, without government approval, claimed the entire area between Canada's eastern and western borders all the way to the [[North Pole]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=MacEachern |first=Alan |year=2010 |title=J.E. Bernier's Claims to Fame |journal=Scientia Canadensis: Canadian Journal of the History of Science, Technology and Medicine |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=43–73 |location=[[Ottawa]] |publisher=Canadian Science and Technology Historical Association |isbn= |issn=0829-2507 |doi=10.7202/1006150ar |accessdate=3 August 2012 |url=http://history.uwo.ca/faculty/maceachern/Erudit,%20MacEachern,%20JE%20Bernier%27s%20Claims%20to%20Fame.pdf }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Bernier only left the ship during the [[World War I|First World War]], returning to command ''Arctic'' again from 1922–1925.<ref name=maginley/> The vessel's end is not agreed upon. According to ''schiffe-und-mehr.com'', ''Arctic'' was abandoned in 1925 and left to rot at her moorings.<ref name="schiffe-und-mehr"/> Maginley and Collin claim the vessel was [[Ship breaking|broken up]] in 1926 while the Miramar Ship Index say the ship was abandoned in 1927.<ref name=miramar/><ref name=maginley/> {{clearleft}}
==Notes== {{notes |notes= {{efn |name=measurements |The [[Wikipedia:Miramar|Miramar Ship Index]] and Maginley and Collin have the ship's [[length between perpendiculars]] as {{convert|50.4|m|ft|abbr=on|1}} and its beam as {{convert|11.3|m|ft|abbr=on|1}}.<ref name=miramar/><ref name=maginley/> }} {{efn |name=power |Maginley and Collin have the vessel's engine rated at {{convert|44|hp|kW|abbr=on}} ([[Horsepower#Nominal (or rated) horsepower (nhp or rhp)|nominal]]). }} }}
