d [[Missouri]], as well as across Kansas and Oklahoma. |- | [[June 12–13, 2013 derecho series]] | {{sort|0612|June 12–13}} | {{sort|036|2013}} | [[Midwest]], [[Southern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 26 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | | Widespread severe weather event began with a few strong tornadoes in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], including an EF3 that caused major damage in the [[Belmond, Iowa|Belmond]] area. Storms grew into a large [[derecho]] with numerous embedded weak tornadoes. A second derecho the following day produced a few embedded tornadoes as well. |- | [[October 2013 North American storm complex]] | {{sort|1003|October 3–7}} | {{sort|037|2013}} | [[Midwest]], [[Great Plains]] | style="text-align:center;"| 22 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | [[File:October 2013 North American storm complex tornado map.png|125px]] | Powerful and dynamic storm system produced a small but intense late-season tornado outbreak, mainly across [[Nebraska]] and [[Iowa]]. Two of the tornadoes reached EF4 intensity, including one that caused severe damage in [[Wayne, Nebraska]]. Other strong tornadoes struck [[Creighton, Nebraska|Creighton]] and [[Macy, Nebraska|Macy]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of November 17, 2013]] | {{sort|1117|November 17}} | {{sort|038|2013}} | [[Midwest]] | style="text-align:center;"| 73 | style="text-align:center;"| 8 | | Many large and strong to violent tornadoes touched down across [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], [[Ohio]] and [[Kentucky]]. Two EF4s struck Illinois, one of which devastated the town of [[Washington, Illinois|Washington]] and killed three people. The other impacted the [[New Minden, Illinois|New Minden]] area, killing 2 others. An EF3 struck [[Brookport, Illinois|Brookport]], killing three people. The outbreak produced the only known violent (EF4–EF5) tornadoes to strike Illinois in the month of November. |- | [[April 2014 North Carolina tornado outbreak]] | {{sort|0425|April 25}} | {{sort|039|2014}} | [[North Carolina]] | style="text-align:center;"| 11 | style="text-align:center;"| 1 | [[File:April 2014 North Carolina tornado outbreak map.png|125px]] | Localized but intense outbreak produced an EF3 that caused major damage near the town of [[Washington, North Carolina|Washington]]. An EF2 in [[Edenton, North Carolina|Edenton]] resulted in a fatality. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of April 27–30, 2014]] | {{sort|0427|April 27–30}} | {{sort|040|2014}} | [[Midwest]], [[Southern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 84 | style="text-align:center;"| 35 | [[File:April 27–30, 2014 tornado outbreak map.png|125px]] | Deadly outbreak that mainly affected the [[Dixie Alley]]. A high-end EF4 devastated the towns of [[Mayflower, Arkansas|Mayflower]] and [[Vilonia, Arkansas]], killing 16. Another EF4 killed 10 people and caused major damage in [[Louisville, Mississippi]]. An EF3 killed 2 when a trailer park was destroyed in [[Coxey, Alabama]]. Another EF3 struck [[Tupelo, Mississippi]], killing 1 and causing severe damage. Many other strong tornadoes also occurred. |- | [[Tornadoes of 2014#May 10–12|Tornado outbreak of May 10–12, 2014]] | {{sort|0407|May 10–12}} | {{sort|041|2014}} | [[Great Plains]] | style="text-align:center;"| 44 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | | A destructive EF2 damaged 80% of the structures in [[Orrick, Missouri]]. An EF3 caused major damage to farms near [[Sutton, Nebraska]], and another very large EF3 damaged every structure in the town of [[Beaver Crossing, Nebraska]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of June 16–18, 2014]] | {{sort|0616|June 16–18}} | {{sort|042|2014}} | [[Midwest]] | style="text-align:center;"| 76 | style="text-align:center;"| 2 | | Outbreak spawned a cyclic supercell in Nebraska that produced four consecutive EF4s, including two twin tornadoes that devastated the town of [[Pilger, Nebraska|Pilger]] and surrounding areas, killing 2. Three nighttime tornadoes (including an EF3) struck [[Madison, Wisconsin]], and its suburbs. A large and slow-moving EF3 clipped the town of [[Coleridge, Nebraska]]. An EF2 caused major damage in [[Wessington Springs, South Dakota]], and a violent EF4 obliterated a farm outside of [[Alpena, South Dakota|Alpena]]. |- | [[December 2014 tornado outbreak|Tornado outbreak of December 23–24, 2014]] | {{sort|1223|December 23–24}} | {{sort|043|2014}} | [[Southern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 10 | style="text-align:center;"| 5 | | Small but damaging outbreak produced a large EF3 that caused major damage in [[Columbia, Mississippi]], and killed 3 people. An EF2 killed 2 others near [[Laurel, Mississippi|Laurel]]. Another EF2 caused considerable damage near [[Amite, Louisiana]]. |- | [[2015 Rochelle–Fairdale, Illinois tornado]] | {{sort|0408|April 8–9}} | {{sort|044|2015}} | [[Midwestern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 24 | style="text-align:center;"| 2 | |Long-tracked, very high-end EF4 tornado moved across several counties in northern [[Illinois]], causing major damage near [[Rochelle, Illinois|Rochelle]] and devastating the small town of [[Fairdale, Illinois|Fairdale]], where two people were killed. Was part of a relatively small outbreak of mostly weak tornadoes, though an EF2 caused considerable damage near [[Mount Selman, Texas]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 5–10, 2015]] | {{sort|0505|May 5–10}} | {{sort|045|2015}} | [[Great Plains]] | style="text-align:center;"| 127 | style="text-align:center;"| 5 | | EF3s caused major damage in [[Bridge Creek, Oklahoma]] and [[Oklahoma City]]. A large EF3 caused significant damage and killed one person near [[Cisco, Texas]], and a high-end EF2 severely damaged the town of [[Delmont, South Dakota]]. A nighttime EF3 killed two people and caused major damage in [[Van, Texas]], while an EF2 killed two more at a mobile home park in [[Nashville, Arkansas]]. |- | [[2015 Texas–Oklahoma flood and tornado outbreak]] | {{sort|0523|May 23–25}} | {{sort|046|2015}} | [[Great Plains]] | style="text-align:center;"| 75 | style="text-align:center;"| 16 | | Produced a destructive early-morning F3 that devastated the Mexican border city of [[Ciudad Acuña]], killing 14 people. An EF2 killed one person near [[Cameron, Texas]], while an EF3 killed another near [[Blue, Oklahoma]]. This was the largest tornado outbreak of 2015, and was accompanied by catastrophic flooding. |- | [[Tornadoes of 2015#June 22–23|Tornado outbreak of June 22–23, 2015]] | {{sort|0622|June 22–23}} | {{sort|047|2015}} | [[Great Lakes]], [[Midwestern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 28 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | |An EF2 and an EF3 caused significant damage in and around [[Albia, Iowa]]. An EF2 caused major damage in [[Edgington, Illinois]], while another EF2 severely damaged a large campground near [[Sublette, Illinois|Sublette]]. A nighttime EF3 damaged or destroyed numerous homes in [[Coal City, Illinois|Coal City]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of November 16–18, 2015]] | {{sort|1116|November 16–18}} | {{sort|049|2015}} | [[Great Plains]] | style="text-align:center;"| 61 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | | Unusual nocturnal late-season tornado outbreak spawned multiple strong tornadoes across the lower [[Great Plains]] states. Two EF3 tornadoes caused major damage near [[Pampa, Texas]], one of which destroyed a large chemical plant complex. A long-tracked EF3 began near [[Liberal, Kansas]] and dissipated near [[Montezuma, Kansas|Montezuma]], causing significant damage in rural areas. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of December 23–25, 2015]] | {{sort|1226|December 23–25}} | {{sort|050|2015}} | [[Southern United States]], [[Midwestern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 38 | style="text-align:center;"| 13 | | Produced multiple strong to violent long-track tornadoes across [[Mississippi]] and [[Tennessee]], including an EF4 that tracked through parts of both states, causing major damage in [[Holly Springs, Mississippi]] and killing 9 people along its path. A high-end EF3 caused major damage near [[Clarksdale, Mississippi|Clarksdale]] as well, killing two. Another EF3 destroyed many structures in the small community of [[Lutts, Tennessee]], and an EF2 killed two people near [[Linden, Tennessee|Linden]]. A high-end EF2 caused considerable damage in the southwestern part of [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. |- | [[December 2015 North American storm complex]] | {{sort|1226|December 26–28}} | {{sort|051|2015}} | [[Southern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 32 | style="text-align:center;"| 13 | | Outbreak of 32 tornadoes severely impacted the [[Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex]]. A large EF4 devastated parts of [[Garland, Texas|Garland]] and [[Rowlett, Texas|Rowlett]], killing 10 people. An EF3 destroyed many homes in [[Ovilla, Texas|Ovilla]] and [[Glenn Heights, Texas|Glenn Heights]], while an EF2 killed two people in [[Copeville, Texas|Copeville]]. An EF1 killed caused a fatality near [[Blue Ridge, Texas|Blue Ridge]] as well. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of February 23–24, 2016]] | {{sort|0223|February 23–24}} | {{sort|052|2016}} | [[Southern United States]], [[Eastern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 61 | style="text-align:center;"| 7 | | The second largest February tornado outbreak on record produced many significant tornadoes across the [[Gulf Coast]] and [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] states. An EF2 caused major damage in [[Laplace, Louisiana]]. An EF3 caused major damage in [[Paincourtville, Louisiana|Paincourtville]] and [[Convent, Louisiana]], killing two people, while an EF2 killed one person near [[Purvis, Mississippi]]. An EF3 caused severe damage in [[Pensacola, Florida]], and an EF1 killed 3 people in [[Waverly, Virginia]]. An EF3 also destroyed multiple homes near [[Tappahannock, Virginia]], while another EF3 killed one person in [[Evergreen, Virginia|Evergreen]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of May 7–10, 2016]] | {{sort|0507|May 7–10}} | {{sort|053|2016}} | [[Western United States]], [[Great Plains]], [[Ohio Valley]] | style="text-align:center;"| 57 | style="text-align:center;"| 2 | | Four-day outbreak of 57 tornadoes produced a high-end EF2 tornado near [[Wray, Colorado]]. A violent EF4 tornado killed one person near [[Katie, Oklahoma]], a damaging EF3 wedge tornado destroyed numerous homes near [[Sulphur, Oklahoma|Sulphur]], and an EF3 caused another fatality near [[Bromide, Oklahoma|Bromide]]. The town of [[Mayfield, Kentucky]] sustained major damage from an EF3 tornado as well. |- | [[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 22–26, 2016]] | {{sort|0522|May 22–26}} | {{sort|054|2016}} | [[Western United States]], [[Great Plains]] | style="text-align:center;"| 98 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | | Outbreak sequence produced numerous strong tornadoes across the Great Plains. Numerous significant tornadoes spawned by a cyclic supercell thunderstorm caused heavy damage near [[Dodge City, Kansas]]. EF3 tornadoes also caused damage near [[Big Spring, Texas|Big Spring]], [[Turkey, Texas|Turkey]] and [[Garden City, Texas]]. An EF4 wedge tornado caused major damage near [[Abeline, Kansas|Abeline]] and [[Chapman, Kansas]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of August 24, 2016]] | {{sort|0824|August 24}} | {{sort|055|2016}} | [[Indiana]], [[Ohio]], [[Ontario]] | style="text-align:center;"| 23 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | | Unexpected and unusual late-season tornado outbreak produced an EF3 that severely damaged or destroyed many homes and businesses in [[Kokomo, Indiana]]. Another EF3 caused major damage to farms near [[Woodburn, Indiana]]. EF2 tornadoes inflicted heavy damage near [[Cecil, Ohio|Cecil]] and [[Defiance, Ohio]], while another EF2 severely damaged structures in [[Windsor, Ontario]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of November 27–30, 2016]] | {{sort|1127|November 27-30}} | {{sort|056|2016}} | [[Central United States]], [[Southern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 46 | style="text-align:center;"| 6 | | Four-day outbreak produced several strong nighttime tornadoes in [[Dixie Alley]]. An EF3 killed 4 people and caused major damage in [[Rosalie, Alabama|Rosalie]] and near [[Ider, Alabama]]. Another EF3 killed two people and severely damaged the town of [[Ocoee, Tennessee]], while a high-end EF2 caused major damage to homes in businesses in [[Athens, Tennessee|Athens]]. An EF2 caused considerable damage at the eastern fringes of [[Huntsville, Alabama]], and an EF3 destroyed several structures near [[Neel, Alabama|Neel]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of January 21–23, 2017]] | {{sort|0121|January 21-23}} | {{sort|057|2017}} | [[Southeastern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 81 | style="text-align:center;"| 20 | | This was the second-deadliest and second largest January tornado outbreak on since reliable records began in 1950, as well as the largest tornado outbreak on record in the state of Georgia. An early morning EF3 produced major damage in [[Hattiesburg, Mississippi]], killing 4. An EF3 near [[Adel, Georgia]] obliterated a mobile home park and killed 11 people along its path, while a large EF3 wedge tornado struck [[Albany, Georgia|Albany]] and killed 5. Many other strong tornadoes caused damage across the Southern United States as well. |- | [[2017 New Orleans tornado]] | {{sort|0207|February 7}} | {{sort|058|2017}} | [[Southeastern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 15 | style="text-align:center;"| 1 | | An EF3 tornado caused major damage in eastern New Orleans, making it the strongest tornado ever recorded in the city's history. Was part of a localized outbreak of tornadoes that impacted the Southern United States, mainly Louisiana. An EF2 caused damage near [[Killian, Louisiana]], while an EF3 occurred near [[Watson, Louisiana|Watson]]. An EF1 struck the town of [[Donaldsonville, Louisiana|Donaldsonville]], killing one person there. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of February 28 – March 1, 2017]] | {{sort|0228|February 28 – March 1}} | {{sort|059|2017}} | [[Midwestern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 72 | style="text-align:center;"| 4 | | A major tornado outbreak occurred across portions of the Midwestern United States and Ohio Valley, leading to 72 tornadoes in total. EF3 tornadoes destroyed homes in and around [[Washburn, Illinois|Washburn]] and [[Ottawa, Illinois]], with two people killed in Ottawa. A long-track EF3 killed one person near [[Crossville, Illinois|Crossville]] as well. The most significant tornado was a long-track EF4 that caused major damage in the [[Perryville, Missouri]] area and killed one person. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of March 6–7, 2017]] | {{sort|0306|March 6–7}} | {{sort|60|2017}} | [[Midwestern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 63 | style="text-align:center;"| 0 | | Following a significant outbreak just a week prior, a second tornado outbreak affected many of the same areas. Many homes were damaged or destroyed in the town of [[Oak Grove, Jackson County, Missouri|Oak Grove, Missouri]] as a result of an EF3 tornado. An EF1 that struck near [[Bricelyn, Minnesota]] was the earliest in state history. EF2 tornadoes caused heavy damage in the Iowa towns of [[Seymour, Iowa|Seymour]], [[Centerville, Iowa|Centerville]], and [[Muscatine, Iowa|Muscatine]]. A long-track EF2 tornado also struck [[Parthenon, Arkansas]]. |- | [[Tornado outbreak and floods of April 28 – May 1, 2017]] |{{sort|0429|April 28 – May 1}} | {{sort|61|2017}} | [[Southeastern United States]], [[Central United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 69 | style="text-align:center;"| 5 | | This outbreak affected the [[Southeastern United States]] and portions of [[Central United States]]. Two destructive wedge tornadoes; rated EF3 and EF4 affected areas outside of [[Canton, Texas]], killing two people each. An EF2 struck the town of [[Durant, Mississippi]] and killed one person as well. The outbreak was accompanied by deadly flooding. |- | [[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 15–20, 2017]] |{{sort|0515|May 15 – May 20}} | {{sort|62|2017}} | [[Central United States]], [[Great Lakes]], [[Ohio Valley]] | style="text-align:center;"| 134 | style="text-align:center;"| 2 | | Large tornado outbreak sequence produced the longest-tracked tornado in Wisconsin history; an EF3 that caused major damage near [[Chetek, Wisconsin|Chetek]] and [[Conrath, Wisconsin|Conrath]]. An EF3 caused severe damage in [[Pawnee Rock, Kansas|Pawnee Rock]] and near [[Great Bend, Kansas]]. A high-end EF2 destroyed homes and businesses in the southern part of [[Elk City, Oklahoma]], killing one person. Another EF2 struck [[Muskogee, Oklahoma]], and many other weak tornadoes also occurred. |- | [[Tornado outbreak of April 13–15, 2018]] |{{sort|0413|April 13 – April 15}} | {{sort|63|2018}} | [[Southern United States]], [[Eastern United States]] | style="text-align:center;"| 70 | style="text-align:center;"| 1 | | This tornado outbreak produced multiple strong tornadoes throughout the Southern and Eastern United States. A large EF2 caused significant damage in [[Mountainburg, Arkansas]], and another EF2 severely impacted [[Meridian, Mississippi]]. An EF1 killed one person in [[Red Chute, Louisiana]], and a high-end EF2 caused major damage in [[Greensboro, North Carolina]]. An EF3 destroyed many homes in [[Elon, Virginia]] as well. |}
