{{see|List of mountain peaks of Mexico}}
{{see also|List of the ultra-prominent summits of North America}}

[[Image:Pico Orizaba Pines.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Pico de Orizaba]] ([[Citlaltépetl]]), a [[stratovolcano]] on the boundary between the states of [[Puebla]] and [[Veracruz]], is the [[Elevation|highest]] [[Summit|mountain peak]] of [[Mexico|México]].]]

The following sortable table comprises the '''26 [[Ultra-prominent peak|ultra-prominent summits]] of [[Mexico|México]]'''.  Each of these peaks has at least {{convert|1500|m|-3|abbr=off|sp=us}} of [[topographic prominence]].<ref name=major>This article defines a significant summit as a summit with at least {{convert|100|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} of [[topographic prominence]], and a major summit as a summit with at least {{convert|500|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} of topographic prominence.  An [[Ultra-prominent peak|ultra-prominent summit]] is a summit with at least {{convert|1500|m|-3|abbr=off|sp=us}} of topographic prominence.</ref>

The [[summit]] of a mountain or hill may be measured in three principal ways:
#The [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] of a summit measures the height of the summit above a [[Geoid|geodetic sea level]].<ref name=range>If the elevation or prominence of a summit is calculated as a range of values, the [[arithmetic mean]] is shown.</ref>
#The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is a measure of how high the summit rises above its surroundings.<ref name=prominence>The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is the [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] difference between the summit and its [[Topographic prominence#Definitions|highest or key col to a higher summit]].  The summit may be near its key col or quite far away.  The key col for [[Denali]] in [[Alaska]] is the [[Isthmus of Rivas]] in [[Nicaragua]], {{convert|7642|km|0|abbr=off|sp=us}} away.</ref><ref name=range/>
#The [[topographic isolation]] (or radius of dominance) of a summit measures how far the summit lies from its nearest point of equal elevation.<ref name=isolation>The [[topographic isolation]] of a summit is the [[great-circle distance]] to its nearest point of equal elevation.</ref>

[[Pico de Orizaba]] exceeds {{convert|4000|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} of topographic prominence, [[Popocatépetl]] exceeds {{convert|3000|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, and [[Nevado de Colima]] exceeds {{convert|2500|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.  Seven mountain peaks of México exceed {{convert|2000|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, the following 26 ultra-prominent summits exceed {{convert|1500|m|-1|abbr=off|sp=us}}, and 42 summits exceed {{convert|1000|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} of topographic prominence.

__TOC__{{clear}}

==Ultra-prominent summits==
{{GeoGroup|section=Ultra-prominent summits}}
{{main|List of the most prominent summits of Mexico}}
Of these 26 ultra-prominent summits of Mexico, four are located in Puebla, four in Oaxaca, four in Nuevo León, three in México, three in Jalisco, two in Veracruz, two in Michoacán, two in Baja California Sur, two in Coahuila, and one each in Morelos, Guerrero, Baja California, Tlaxcala, and Querétaro.  Four of these peaks lie on a state border.
{{clear}}
