[[lt:Pasaulio šalių didmiesčiai]]

[[File:Monaco Ville from Tête de Chien - panoramio.jpg|thumb|260px|View of the Rock from Tête de Chien]]
The '''Rock of Monaco''' ({{lang-fr|Rocher de Monaco}}) is a {{convert|62|m|ft|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Provence 7 Monaco-Ville|url=http://www.provence7.com/a-a-z-des-articles/monaco-ville-a-visiter/|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref> tall [[monolith]] on the [[Mediterranean]] coast of the [[Monaco|Principality of Monaco]]. It overlooks the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and the port.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rock of Monaco|url=http://travel.viamichelin.com/web/Destination/France-French_Alps-French_Riviera_and_Monaco-Monaco/Tourist_Site-The_Rock_of_Monaco-Avenue_St_Martin|publisher=Michelin|accessdate=9 August 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609165545/http://travel.viamichelin.com/web/Destination/France-French_Alps-French_Riviera_and_Monaco-Monaco/Tourist_Site-The_Rock_of_Monaco-Avenue_St_Martin|archivedate=9 June 2011|df=}}</ref>
==History== The Rock has been a coveted possession from the beginning of the ancient [[Marseilles|Massilia]]n colony of Monoïkos ([[Ancient Greek Language|Greek]]: Μόνοικος), named for the [[Ligures|Ligurian]] tribes who occupied the area and vied for control of it; even earlier, it was a shelter for primitive populations. The Rock of [[Monaco]] was also the first conquest of the [[House of Grimaldi|Grimaldi]] dynasty, the rulers of the country for more than 700 years, founded when the [[Guelf]] [[François Grimaldi|Francesco Grimaldi]] disguised himself as a Franciscan monk in order to gain entry to the city and open the gates for his soldiers.
==Today== Today, the Rock is in the oldest of Monaco's four quarters, [[Monaco-Ville]], which is also the location of Old Town, the oldest part of the city. This is not far from the [[Prince's Palace of Monaco|Prince's Palace]] ({{lang-fr|Le Palais Princier}}), home of the current [[monarch]] [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco|Albert II]] and the [[Monegasque Princely Family|princely family]], the [[Saint Nicholas Cathedral, Monaco|Cathedral]] and the [[Oceanographic Museum of Monaco]]. The Rock of Monaco is a popular attraction where tourists view the palace and the changing of the guards.
==Image gallery== <gallery widths="155px" heights="130px"> Image:Monacoc1890.jpg|The Rock in 1890 File:Monaco003.jpg|Monaco-Ville and harbour of Fontvieille today </gallery>
